</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="153" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="153">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="153">
Female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1895" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Meotipa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Meotipa" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">Meotipa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from all other theridiids by the conspicuous flattened black spines on the abdomen and/or legs. Therefore, they are often referred to as spiny theridiids. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1895" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Meotipa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Meotipa" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">Meotipa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males are significantly smaller than females. The male palp of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1895" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Meotipa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Meotipa" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">Meotipa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other theridiids by the spoon-shaped conductor and embolus being thin and short, with the straight base, completely surrounded by the spoon-shaped conductor or the tip of embolus, which is opposite to the conductor (except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Deeleman-Reinhold" authorityYear="2009" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Meotipa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Meotipa bituberculata" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bituberculata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">Meotipa bituberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Deeleman-Reinhold, CL" journalOrPublisher="Contributions to Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" pagination="403 - 436" refId="B6" refString="Deeleman-Reinhold, CL, 2009. Spiny theridiids in the Asian tropics. Systematics, notes on behaviour and species richness (Araneae: Theridiidae: Chrysso, Meotipa). Contributions to Natural History 12: 403 - 436" title="Spiny theridiids in the Asian tropics. Systematics, notes on behaviour and species richness (Araneae: Theridiidae: Chrysso, Meotipa)." volume="12" year="2009">Deeleman-Reinhold 2009</bibRefCitation>
: 419, figs 20-37). The species included in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1895" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Meotipa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Meotipa" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">Meotipa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are given below, with their distributions.
</paragraph>
